00:12:00,280 --> 00:12:05,764
This time around we have to kind of up the level of nastiness in the enemies.

250
00:12:05,764 --> 00:12:09,066
They're up to no good, they're going to kill her.

251
00:12:09,066 --> 00:12:14,230
She's very much in a mode, very focused on what she's doing,

252
00:12:14,230 --> 00:12:21,155
and she's much more able to meet fire with fire than she was in the first game.

253
00:12:21,155 --> 00:12:23,397
So, yeah, making the enemies more violent,

254
00:12:23,397 --> 00:12:28,461
making her not killing innocents and giving her a bit of a moral compass

255
00:12:28,461 --> 00:12:29,782
really helped with that sort of...

256
00:12:30,433 --> 00:12:31,473
player synchronicity.

257
00:12:31,473 --> 00:12:35,916
So using those learnings from 2013's Tomb Raider as well as our Crystal Dynamics story

258
00:12:35,916 --> 00:12:42,439
pillars, I want to talk a little bit about our process and sort of eight basic steps.

259
00:12:42,439 --> 00:12:46,321
Hopefully you'll see how those story pillars and those learnings that we attempted to bring

260
00:12:46,321 --> 00:12:51,243
into Rise of the Tomb Raider really informed our decision making throughout the whole process.

261
00:12:51,243 --> 00:12:53,564
So Noah, what is the very beginning of our process?

262
00:12:54,935 --> 00:12:58,480
Yeah, it starts with some high concept discussion.

263
00:12:58,480 --> 00:13:01,264
So we know we want to tell the next chapter in Lara's story.

264
00:13:01,264 --> 00:13:04,329
One of the techniques we use to sort of build

265
00:13:04,329 --> 00:13:06,492
that foundation for Lara, especially

266
00:13:06,492 --> 00:13:08,836
her internal conflict and her journey as a character.

267
00:13:09,897 --> 00:13:11,479
is this controlling idea.

268
00:13:11,479 --> 00:13:14,543
So what that does is suggest that there's a key value

269
00:13:14,543 --> 00:13:18,668
at stake and some action is going to change that value.

270
00:13:18,668 --> 00:13:21,191
In particular, to give our example,

271
00:13:21,191 --> 00:13:24,054
we made the statement, we become who we are meant to be

272
00:13:24,054 --> 00:13:26,037
when we let go of who we are supposed to be.

273
00:13:26,637 --> 00:13:35,479
So this is not only thematic, but it defines the actions that Lara takes, and ultimately the result of that is the forging of her identity.

274
00:13:35,479 --> 00:13:42,360
So identity is what's at stake in this story, and Lara comes into it with this notion that she is a discoverer,

275
00:13:42,360 --> 00:13:47,681
that she is going to find something great and bring it back to the world, and that is going to make the world a better place.

276
00:13:47,681 --> 00:13:52,442
But over the course of the story, she has to confront what her actions will result in,

277
00:13:52,442 --> 00:13:54,842
and ultimately through doing that will...

278
00:13:56,042 --> 00:13:59,103
to redefine her relationship with these ancient secrets

279
00:13:59,103 --> 00:14:01,124
that she's pursuing.

280
00:14:01,124 --> 00:14:04,244
This is also a theme that runs through other facets

281
00:14:04,244 --> 00:14:04,745
of the game.

282
00:14:04,745 --> 00:14:07,525
So in a lot of ways, the story becomes

283
00:14:07,525 --> 00:14:10,246
sort of a debate over this facet of the human condition,

284
00:14:10,246 --> 00:14:14,627
that should you fulfill your destiny as you believed it was,

285
00:14:14,627 --> 00:14:18,008
or should you let go of that and sort of jump and become

286
00:14:18,008 --> 00:14:19,288
that new person?

287
00:14:19,288 --> 00:14:21,209
And that's something that we see not only in Lara,

288
00:14:21,209 --> 00:14:24,350
but our additional characters, the remnants.

289
00:14:24,770 --> 00:14:27,512
who are defined as protectors of this secret.

290
00:14:27,512 --> 00:14:28,453
And by the end of that,

291
00:14:28,453 --> 00:14:30,394
they have to change their relationship,

292
00:14:30,394 --> 00:14:32,056
and ultimately in doing so,

293
00:14:32,056 --> 00:14:33,757
sort of move forward as a people.

294
00:14:33,757 --> 00:14:36,599
So this is a theme that helps guide us through,

295
00:14:36,599 --> 00:14:38,161
even as we go through many iterations,

296
00:14:38,161 --> 00:14:39,342
which we'll talk about,

297
00:14:39,342 --> 00:14:42,064
we sort of have this notion of what our story is,

298
00:14:42,064 --> 00:14:42,864
is really about.

299
00:14:43,961 --> 00:14:49,527
Yeah, and with that, we can start doing research on the plot.

300
00:14:49,527 --> 00:14:52,070
And in our case, it's the myth.

301
00:14:52,070 --> 00:14:54,212
What is Lara going after?

302
00:14:54,212 --> 00:14:55,253
We know what kind of drives her.

303
00:14:55,253 --> 00:14:56,695
We know the kind of debate she's going

304
00:14:56,695 --> 00:14:57,916
to have in her character arc.

305
00:14:57,916 --> 00:15:00,619
So we were looking at myths that had

306
00:15:02,040 --> 00:15:05,322
you know, danger as well as benefit to humanity.

307
00:15:05,322 --> 00:15:07,663
So that choice that she makes,

308
00:15:07,663 --> 00:15:08,843
there's a bit of a gray area there.

309
00:15:08,843 --> 00:15:10,124
It's kind of like the atom, you know,

310
00:15:10,124 --> 00:15:11,865
that you can make an atom bomb

311
00:15:11,865 --> 00:15:13,185
or you can create limitless energy.

312
00:15:13,185 --> 00:15:15,466
This idea that, you know, what she's going after

313
00:15:15,466 --> 00:15:17,407
will cause a debate for her.

314
00:15:17,407 --> 00:15:20,348
And since she kind of encountered an immortality myth

315
00:15:20,348 --> 00:15:21,188
in the first game,

316
00:15:21,188 --> 00:15:23,509
like this kind of crazy soul-sucking Japanese queen,

317
00:15:24,410 --> 00:15:27,312
We assumed that she's going to be interested in that idea of immortality.

318
00:15:27,312 --> 00:15:29,333
So we started looking at immortality myths.

319
00:15:29,333 --> 00:15:32,275
These are some of the ones we kind of discarded out of hand.

320
00:15:32,275 --> 00:15:33,776
Not out of hand, we did some research.

321
00:15:33,776 --> 00:15:37,579
But, you know, there was Noah's Ark and Fountain of Youth and Garden of Eden.

322
00:15:37,579 --> 00:15:40,281
For various reasons, these didn't really work for us.

323
00:15:40,281 --> 00:15:43,763
So we landed on two myths that we kind of mashed together.

324
00:15:43,763 --> 00:15:48,726
The city, Velocity of Kitezh, which is sort of unknown in popular culture,

325
00:15:48,726 --> 00:15:49,867
at least in the West.

326
00:15:49,867 --> 00:15:51,748
We had this guy on the team from Russia who was like, oh,

327
00:15:51,748 --> 00:15:53,249
my grandmother used to tell me this story.

328
00:15:53,850 --> 00:15:59,031
So it's quite popular in the East, but it's basically this Atlantis of the East,

329
00:15:59,031 --> 00:16:01,152
this city that sinks into a lake and disappears.

330
00:16:01,152 --> 00:16:04,212
And it was a great setting for us because we could build tombs out of this.

331
00:16:04,212 --> 00:16:06,893
It has connections to history.

332
00:16:06,893 --> 00:16:12,154
And the other myth that was important for us was this myth of Koschei the Deathless,

333
00:16:12,154 --> 00:16:12,234
who

334
00:16:13,235 --> 00:16:18,500
was another obscure Russian myth, maybe not so obscure to some people, but this myth is

335
00:16:18,500 --> 00:16:22,925
about a man who takes his soul, puts it in an object, and attains immortality.

336
00:16:22,925 --> 00:16:26,629
And so that gave us a nice MacGuffin for Lara to go after, what is this object?

337
00:16:26,629 --> 00:16:30,973
But also gave us another interesting character, and we actually didn't use Kostya, the actual

338
00:16:30,973 --> 00:16:33,296
name, we just based our character Jacob on him.

339
00:16:33,676 --> 00:16:36,477
This idea that Jacob has something to lose as well,

340
00:16:36,477 --> 00:16:39,198
something that he has to debate in his arc.

341
00:16:39,198 --> 00:16:42,660
So by the end, when he gives up his immortality,

342
00:16:42,660 --> 00:16:45,381
he becomes who he's meant to be, which is dead.

343
00:16:48,779 --> 00:16:52,181
And the immortality myths also gave us a nice lens to look at

344
00:16:52,181 --> 00:16:53,722
Laura's relationship with her father.

345
00:16:53,722 --> 00:16:54,662
Absolutely.

346
00:16:54,662 --> 00:16:55,042
Yes.

347
00:16:55,042 --> 00:16:55,362
Yes.

348
00:16:55,362 --> 00:16:58,804
Forgot about that note, but yes, so we, we basically mirrored that on her father

349
00:16:58,804 --> 00:17:02,426
as well, because that's a primary motivator for Laura and she's, she's not

350
00:17:02,426 --> 00:17:06,288
only trying to find this, this, this ancient secret and prove it to the world.

351
00:17:06,288 --> 00:17:08,949
She's also kind of trying to live up to her father.

352
00:17:08,949 --> 00:17:08,989
So.

353
00:17:11,531 --> 00:17:14,894
So after we'd sort of established the high concept,

354
00:17:14,894 --> 00:17:17,115
it was time to sort of move on to the treatment.

355
00:17:17,115 --> 00:17:21,318
And our treatments are similar to what you might find

356
00:17:21,318 --> 00:17:22,138
in a movie treatment.

357
00:17:22,138 --> 00:17:24,800
They're sort of halfway between a traditional movie treatment

358
00:17:24,800 --> 00:17:27,342
and something that's very game specific.

359
00:17:27,342 --> 00:17:31,104
So the treatment was about nailing down the broad strokes,

360
00:17:31,104 --> 00:17:34,307
Lara's arc, looking at all the characters.

361
00:17:34,307 --> 00:17:36,088
We spent a lot of time focusing on the characters

362
00:17:36,088 --> 00:17:37,569
and their wants and their needs,

363
00:17:37,569 --> 00:17:39,050
which are often different things,

364
00:17:39,050 --> 00:17:39,590
and how does the...

365
00:17:40,531 --> 00:17:46,834
The gameplay and the story clash with those wants and needs and how they tie into everyone else.

366
00:17:46,834 --> 00:17:51,376
And so we were sort of putting that together with the broad strokes, with the arc.

367
00:17:51,376 --> 00:17:56,958
And that was largely myself and John and Noah and some special guests from Square and XHQ,

368
00:17:56,958 --> 00:18:00,940
just really sitting in a room kind of hashing everything out.

369
00:18:01,455 --> 00:18:05,197
and then kind of me just sitting and pulling everything together into a document,

370
00:18:05,197 --> 00:18:08,158
which helped guide the first part of the production process.

371
00:18:08,158 --> 00:18:10,399
And from that we could sort of start putting together a skeleton.

372
00:18:19,834 --> 00:18:21,416
of the script, sorry.

373
00:18:21,416 --> 00:18:25,640
And from those, I could do more of an outline.

374
00:18:25,640 --> 00:18:29,083
And as I say, we looked at the characters first and foremost.

375
00:18:29,083 --> 00:18:30,965
And because we had fewer characters to deal with,

376
00:18:30,965 --> 00:18:32,826
we could make them count.

377
00:18:32,826 --> 00:18:34,548
We could spend a lot of time focusing

378
00:18:34,548 --> 00:18:36,850
on how their particular journeys intersected

379
00:18:36,850 --> 00:18:38,171
and how they affected one another.

380
00:18:39,212 --> 00:18:43,796
So, you know, I went back and I looked over all the documents that we had done at the time

381
00:18:43,796 --> 00:18:49,441
because you produce so much and you iterate so much, it's very difficult to remember where you came from.

382
00:18:49,441 --> 00:18:55,926
But a lot of our ideas that we were doing at this stage made it through to the end game in some form.

383
00:18:55,926 --> 00:19:01,671
But one of the ones I missed in particular was when we blew up UCL's archaeology department.

384
00:19:02,352 --> 00:19:04,656
which terrified and excited me in equal measure.

385
00:19:04,656 --> 00:19:06,018
And that was in the script for a while,

386
00:19:06,018 --> 00:19:07,661
but that was kind of one of the ones

387
00:19:07,661 --> 00:19:09,063
I sort of missed a little bit, to be honest.

388
00:19:12,128 --> 00:19:17,889
Okay, so once we have a treatment and we've got our bedrock of controlling idea, we go

389
00:19:17,889 --> 00:19:22,110
into what we call our metascripting phase, and that's what we call it. I don't know if

390
00:19:22,110 --> 00:19:28,291
we can coin that term, but we do a lot of exercises to start bringing the story to a

391
00:19:28,291 --> 00:19:33,772
state where we can start making a game. And the first thing we do is we create a giant

392
00:19:33,772 --> 00:19:38,093
Word document, which is sort of a description of every cinematic scene and...

393
00:19:38,513 --> 00:19:43,017
all descriptions of gameplay in just one sort of written document from top to bottom.

394
00:19:43,017 --> 00:19:43,878
And it's about 100 pages.

395
00:19:43,878 --> 00:19:48,902
This is kind of the first place that narrative and gameplay kind of shake hands.

396
00:19:48,902 --> 00:19:50,824
They have a stake in this.

397
00:19:50,824 --> 00:19:54,987
I'm working with our narrative leads, or our game design leads,

398
00:19:54,987 --> 00:19:58,050
and we basically put together a high-level skeleton of,

399
00:19:58,050 --> 00:20:01,573
yeah, this is the story from beginning to end, how it interfaces with gameplay.

400
00:20:01,573 --> 00:20:05,537
We can start looking at pacing, start looking at how much time we're talking about between scenes.

401
00:20:06,057 --> 00:20:10,682
It's great to plan things out, but then you should also plan for it to change, because it's going to change.

402
00:20:10,682 --> 00:20:15,086
And then, from the Metascript, we start creating beat documents, and these are...

403
00:20:15,086 --> 00:20:21,972
they can be considered your standard level design documents, but for us what's important is

404
00:20:21,972 --> 00:20:24,074
these are written experientially, so...

405
00:20:25,856 --> 00:20:28,317
to help the team imagine and visualize the experience

406
00:20:28,317 --> 00:20:32,179
so that they can be inspired to build and inspired to create.

407
00:20:32,179 --> 00:20:34,000
So these aren't, they're kind of blueprints,

408
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:36,101
but they're also inspiration pieces for the team.

409
00:20:36,101 --> 00:20:38,863
We give them to a large group of team responsible

410
00:20:38,863 --> 00:20:40,644
for bringing the levels to life.

411
00:20:40,644 --> 00:20:43,425
And we expect these to come back to us as leads

412
00:20:43,425 --> 00:20:45,967
or as a narrative team with changes or ideas

413
00:20:45,967 --> 00:20:47,668
because like I said, the entire team is involved

414
00:20:47,668 --> 00:20:49,909
in the story and we want them to do that.

415
00:20:49,909 --> 00:20:53,311
So this is a guide for them to be creative

416
00:20:53,311 --> 00:20:54,771
and to be, to engage in the story.

417
00:20:55,036 --> 00:20:59,079
And as you mentioned, this is the first time that the story and game player put side by side,

418
00:20:59,079 --> 00:21:00,840
and they really are never decoupled after that.

419
00:21:00,840 --> 00:21:04,282
We always look at them as a holistic experience in concert.

420
00:21:04,282 --> 00:21:11,427
So another exercise for us is, we take all the major character arcs and plot threads

421
00:21:11,427 --> 00:21:14,689
and break them down into their component parts and hashtag them.

422
00:21:15,409 --> 00:21:17,010
and throw them up on a board.

423
00:21:17,010 --> 00:21:19,651
We usually start with just a Post-it board,

424
00:21:19,651 --> 00:21:20,911
and then it goes digital so the team

425
00:21:20,911 --> 00:21:22,032
can access it on the network.

426
00:21:22,032 --> 00:21:25,453
But this allows us to track everything

427
00:21:25,453 --> 00:21:26,433
that's happening in the story.

428
00:21:26,433 --> 00:21:29,654
And this is both a proactive and reactive exercise.

429
00:21:29,654 --> 00:21:31,755
And when we do it initially, it's

430
00:21:31,755 --> 00:21:33,276
liable to change along the process,

431
00:21:33,276 --> 00:21:35,176
and we update it as we go through.

432
00:21:35,176 --> 00:21:37,297
But it's a tool for us to start looking at.

433
00:21:37,857 --> 00:21:41,278
tension, emotional pacing, log jams of ideas.

434
00:21:41,278 --> 00:21:42,939
We might see a scene has 10 hashtags,

435
00:21:42,939 --> 00:21:46,400
and we realize that's going to be a monster scene that

436
00:21:46,400 --> 00:21:47,500
has to have a lot of this stuff.

437
00:21:47,500 --> 00:21:51,542
And it's also a way to inform Rihanna, myself,

438
00:21:51,542 --> 00:21:54,682
the people who are writing the scenes, what's happening.

439
00:21:54,682 --> 00:21:59,344
As an example of how we use this to, I think, great effect.

440
00:22:00,385 --> 00:22:05,691
For a while in our game, we were noticing on our board that the dad hashtag, which you saw in the last one,

441
00:22:05,691 --> 00:22:14,602
the dad hashtag, because her dad is important to her, the arc of her mirroring her father is very much part of her motivation.

442
00:22:15,243 --> 00:22:19,645
And for about two hours, two, three hours in the beginning of the game, it was just gone.

443
00:22:19,645 --> 00:22:21,766
It wasn't anywhere. It wasn't in-game, it wasn't in any scenes.

444
00:22:21,766 --> 00:22:25,507
She talked about him in that first scene, and then there was this gulf.

445
00:22:25,507 --> 00:22:28,589
And people were... we were worried people were just going to lose that thread.

446
00:22:28,589 --> 00:22:32,010
So we came up with this mechanic to bring in-game.

447
00:22:32,010 --> 00:22:33,691
We called it our dictaphone mechanic.

448
00:22:33,691 --> 00:22:35,432
The dictaphone is that thing there.

449
00:22:35,432 --> 00:22:39,494
My dad had one. I don't know if you guys have any idea what this is, but it's a tape recorder.

450
00:22:40,515 --> 00:22:41,095
Where you'd...

451
00:22:41,095 --> 00:22:43,177
Raise your hand if you've used it.

452
00:22:43,177 --> 00:22:43,217
No.

453
00:22:43,217 --> 00:22:44,998
Anyways, she picks us up.

454
00:22:44,998 --> 00:22:45,739
Lara's kind of a lutter.

455
00:22:45,739 --> 00:22:47,600
You've maybe noticed she doesn't even have a phone.

456
00:22:47,600 --> 00:22:48,421
We did that deliberately.

457
00:22:48,421 --> 00:22:51,444
We don't give her a phone because that just opens a whole world of mechanics we don't

458
00:22:51,444 --> 00:22:53,165
want to deal with, like Twitter.

459
00:22:53,165 --> 00:22:58,389
We don't want her to tweet, ah, I found the tomb.

460
00:22:59,175 --> 00:23:01,176
Maybe we'll do that, but I don't know.

461
00:23:01,176 --> 00:23:03,397
So we kind of think of her as a Luddite.

462
00:23:03,397 --> 00:23:04,217
She has this thing.

463
00:23:04,217 --> 00:23:05,658
She's walking around the environment.

464
00:23:05,658 --> 00:23:08,039
We hear dad talking from the past.

465
00:23:08,039 --> 00:23:09,319
They're connected.

466
00:23:09,319 --> 00:23:10,480
It's on the sticks.

467
00:23:10,480 --> 00:23:11,280
It's in her inventory.

468
00:23:11,280 --> 00:23:12,080
It's a mechanic.

469
00:23:12,080 --> 00:23:14,181
So that uptick was great.

470
00:23:14,181 --> 00:23:14,982
It was like, cool.

471
00:23:14,982 --> 00:23:17,543
And we found that with our hashtag board.

472
00:23:17,543 --> 00:23:19,724
We used that as like, oh, we need to put something here.

473
00:23:20,204 --> 00:23:21,606
And it kind of got everyone thinking about,

474
00:23:21,606 --> 00:23:22,608
like, what are the, you know,

475
00:23:22,608 --> 00:23:23,950
instead of just having her say,

476
00:23:23,950 --> 00:23:26,554
dad, in a cinematic, which she does,

477
00:23:26,554 --> 00:23:27,596
we also have something in game.

478
00:23:27,596 --> 00:23:29,499
And we actually probably used it too much.

479
00:23:29,499 --> 00:23:30,480
At some point, the team was like,

480
00:23:30,480 --> 00:23:31,902
she needs to shut up about dad.

481
00:23:31,902 --> 00:23:33,845
Because it was like, dad, dad, dad, let's talk.

482
00:23:33,845 --> 00:23:34,286
Yeah.

483
00:23:37,340 --> 00:23:40,001
And then that leads us to the script.

484
00:23:40,001 --> 00:23:43,983
So another purpose of the meta-script is to basically give me a road map going into the

485
00:23:43,983 --> 00:23:45,124
first draft of the script.

486
00:23:45,124 --> 00:23:49,266
So I write the script more or less like a movie script, so it's usually in chronological

487
00:23:49,266 --> 00:23:52,367
order, which certainly isn't the case for all games, but it's always been for the Tomb

488
00:23:52,367 --> 00:23:53,368
Raider ones.

