00:27:58,646 --> 00:28:02,671
So it helped feed back into the writing team, their ability to be able to kind of streamline

571
00:28:02,671 --> 00:28:03,492
the story.

572
00:28:03,492 --> 00:28:04,012
Absolutely.

573
00:28:04,998 --> 00:28:07,561
Previously, John talked a little bit about the world as a character.

574
00:28:07,561 --> 00:28:09,603
It's one of our major pillars.

575
00:28:09,603 --> 00:28:11,645
Now, the main story obviously focuses on Lara.

576
00:28:11,645 --> 00:28:13,668
But when we talk about the world as a character,

577
00:28:13,668 --> 00:28:16,951
we often talk about something called supporting or secondary narrative.

578
00:28:16,951 --> 00:28:18,973
This includes everything outside of Lara.

579
00:28:18,973 --> 00:28:21,316
This is overheard enemy conversations.

580
00:28:21,316 --> 00:28:23,538
This is collectible relics and documents.

581
00:28:23,538 --> 00:28:25,641
This is the history and the layers in the game.

582
00:28:26,021 --> 00:28:32,330
All of these support Lara's story, but they also flesh out the world and give us a variety of other lenses to look through.

583
00:28:32,330 --> 00:28:38,738
We talk a lot about canvas for narrative, in the sense that everything in the game is a potential to tell some aspect of the story.

584
00:28:38,738 --> 00:28:42,283
Even an animation cycle tells something important about how that character is acting.

585
00:28:42,663 --> 00:28:47,586
SecondaryNative is a great place that we can sort of spread our wings and play in a little bit wider margin.

586
00:28:47,586 --> 00:28:53,489
The main story obviously focuses on Lara, but when we talk about the world, we talk about first layers of history.

587
00:28:53,489 --> 00:28:56,790
And this is something we do through a pretty exhaustive research process.

588
00:28:56,790 --> 00:28:58,531
Once we had our initial myth of Katesh...

589
00:28:58,792 --> 00:29:02,453
and we knew that we were focusing on Russian and Siberian history.

590
00:29:02,453 --> 00:29:04,574
That allowed us to make what we call layers of history.

591
00:29:04,574 --> 00:29:08,055
Now, the first layer, obviously, is Lara and the current story with Trinity,

592
00:29:08,055 --> 00:29:10,596
but just beneath that, about 50 years prior,

593
00:29:10,596 --> 00:29:13,577
we have a Soviet Cold War era layer,

594
00:29:13,577 --> 00:29:17,478
and then beneath that we have the layer of the Remnant living off the land.

595
00:29:17,478 --> 00:29:19,759
Prior to that, there's the layer of the Mongol invasion

596
00:29:19,759 --> 00:29:22,540
and the Golden Age of Kutaish before that.

597
00:29:22,720 --> 00:29:25,664
And then even beneath that there's a layer of ancient history.

598
00:29:25,664 --> 00:29:28,126
Now that ancient history doesn't so much support the main narratives

599
00:29:28,126 --> 00:29:32,171
if it gives Lara a chance to say and think smart things about archaeology,

600
00:29:32,171 --> 00:29:34,253
which helps put another lens on her character.

601
00:29:34,253 --> 00:29:36,836
Obviously the world is telling a story

602
00:29:36,836 --> 00:29:39,839
and always we want to be aware of all the layers of history in every area.

603
00:29:40,600 --> 00:29:44,303
From this amount of research we would create exhaustive documentation.

604
00:29:44,303 --> 00:29:47,566
Sometimes we would create short stories from the point of view of certain characters

605
00:29:47,566 --> 00:29:53,431
that would give a sense of a tone for that area of history that we wanted to explore.

606
00:29:53,431 --> 00:30:00,076
On the right there you'll see a fairly detailed history of the birth of our immortal prophet, Jacob.

607
00:30:00,076 --> 00:30:03,159
Starting with exactly where he was born and what he did as a child.

608
00:30:03,159 --> 00:30:05,881
Now none of this stuff actually made it into the game, but it...

609
00:30:06,102 --> 00:30:09,183
It created a very solid bedrock of real research

610
00:30:09,183 --> 00:30:11,024
that we could connect his life to,

611
00:30:11,024 --> 00:30:13,465
gave us things to hook onto.

612
00:30:13,465 --> 00:30:15,746
We talk a lot about plausible Googleability

613
00:30:15,746 --> 00:30:17,606
when we talk about using history, which

614
00:30:17,606 --> 00:30:20,108
is that we want to include things that people can latch

615
00:30:20,108 --> 00:30:22,308
onto, go right to the internet, and look up,

616
00:30:22,308 --> 00:30:24,369
and at least there's a sense of veracity

617
00:30:24,369 --> 00:30:26,350
that we have connected a real world thing

618
00:30:26,350 --> 00:30:27,971
and then adapted it for a video game.

619
00:30:28,337 --> 00:30:31,360
And the funny thing is, when we were working on the project,

620
00:30:31,360 --> 00:30:32,621
we would try to Google certain things,

621
00:30:32,621 --> 00:30:33,602
and we couldn't get an answer.

622
00:30:33,602 --> 00:30:35,264
So we'd walk over to Cam, and we'd ask him,

623
00:30:35,264 --> 00:30:37,987
and he would pretty much have the answer almost every time.

624
00:30:37,987 --> 00:30:40,229
So after a while, we're like, why Google it?

625
00:30:40,229 --> 00:30:41,931
Just Cam it.

626
00:30:41,931 --> 00:30:44,434
Yeah, unfortunately, Jeff, I was just smiling and Googling

627
00:30:44,434 --> 00:30:45,955
it under the desk.

628
00:30:45,955 --> 00:30:48,077
He types faster, and he could do it without looking.

629
00:30:48,077 --> 00:30:48,278
I'm just like.

630
00:30:48,933 --> 00:30:53,315
So obviously you may not be working on a project that is a historical fiction grounded archaeology

631
00:30:53,315 --> 00:30:58,358
adventure, but it is important that you have a sense of internal consistency and logic

632
00:30:58,358 --> 00:30:59,598
to your world.

633
00:30:59,598 --> 00:31:03,400
And I think research is the place where we create that solid bedrock that we can all

634
00:31:03,400 --> 00:31:05,921
go back to and make sure we're on solid ground.

635
00:31:07,162 --> 00:31:11,384
Bringing these connections into context, this is an interesting story, is during the creation

636
00:31:11,384 --> 00:31:14,606
of the game we knew that we wanted to have an enemy near the end of the game that we

637
00:31:14,606 --> 00:31:19,369
had called internally the Deathless Ones, that were an immortal army that could not

638
00:31:19,369 --> 00:31:20,189
be killed.

639
00:31:20,189 --> 00:31:23,952
Now in my research I discovered that right around the time that we have our immortal

640
00:31:23,952 --> 00:31:30,035
prophet leaving the city of Constantinople, there is also an elite imperial guard called

641
00:31:30,035 --> 00:31:30,816
the Afanatoi.

642
00:31:31,216 --> 00:31:35,379
that vanished from the historical record with the death of one emperor and the ascendancy

643
00:31:35,379 --> 00:31:41,342
of the emperor Basil I. Interestingly, the word athanatoi in Greek literally means without

644
00:31:41,342 --> 00:31:45,745
death. So once I realized that we had a missing army with the exact same name as our army

645
00:31:45,745 --> 00:31:49,688
that we were going to put in the game, it was obviously a no-brainer to combine those

646
00:31:49,688 --> 00:31:53,490
two things. It gave us a historical record that we could base those characters on. The

647
00:31:53,490 --> 00:31:58,073
real historical athanatoi were the sons of noble houses, so they were resplendent in

648
00:31:58,073 --> 00:31:59,694
very non-functional golden armor.

649
00:32:00,034 --> 00:32:02,055
So we use that as a part of an aesthetic guide

650
00:32:02,055 --> 00:32:04,057
in the creation of those characters.

651
00:32:04,057 --> 00:32:07,138
Grounding that foundation in plausible Googleability,

652
00:32:07,138 --> 00:32:09,740
being able to leave the game and look that up in the real world

653
00:32:09,740 --> 00:32:11,381
was something we always strove towards.

654
00:32:12,745 --> 00:32:15,746
And now secondary narrative, I don't want to say that it just

655
00:32:15,746 --> 00:32:17,467
explores the margins of the world.

656
00:32:17,467 --> 00:32:18,907
We also can use secondary narrative

657
00:32:18,907 --> 00:32:23,008
to really clearly focus back on Lara and where she is.

