stand up a new version of the scene.

964
00:47:47,783 --> 00:47:51,145
Jeff's gonna sadly draw it again for the 47th time as well.

965
00:47:51,145 --> 00:47:53,726
Megan's gonna read it again for the 47th time.

966
00:47:53,726 --> 00:47:55,607
And eventually you start getting the results

967
00:47:55,607 --> 00:47:56,888
you want from the story.

968
00:47:56,888 --> 00:47:58,249
Ow, my hand.

969
00:47:58,249 --> 00:47:59,550
Just hurts thinking about it.

970
00:48:01,863 --> 00:48:04,764
Yeah, which leads to the actual performances.

971
00:48:04,764 --> 00:48:06,705
And like Noah was saying, this is

972
00:48:06,705 --> 00:48:10,586
where it gets really expensive and really tough

973
00:48:10,586 --> 00:48:11,287
to change things.

974
00:48:11,287 --> 00:48:15,469
So having that very agile process up to the point

975
00:48:15,469 --> 00:48:18,630
where we go to the set and shoot it,

976
00:48:18,630 --> 00:48:19,090
and even

977
00:48:19,976 --> 00:48:22,017
Like, we try to be prepared, we try to say,

978
00:48:22,017 --> 00:48:24,159
okay, we have to be two days early,

979
00:48:24,159 --> 00:48:25,559
because of everybody's schedules and stuff,

980
00:48:25,559 --> 00:48:29,602
to deliver all the scripts, to deliver the boards,

981
00:48:29,602 --> 00:48:32,044
so we have them on set so the actors can be prepared.

982
00:48:32,044 --> 00:48:34,865
But there were times we would come to the set

983
00:48:34,865 --> 00:48:37,987
with new boards from Jeff that he'd been drawing all night,

984
00:48:37,987 --> 00:48:41,309
stick them on the walls, okay, sorry, we change it again,

985
00:48:41,309 --> 00:48:42,110
and the actors would be...

986
00:48:43,050 --> 00:48:48,272
cool with it it would take a little more time to rehearse it on stage but we were very very

987
00:48:48,272 --> 00:48:54,954
fortunate to have Camilla Luddington as our our star that was very well calibrated from the previous

988
00:48:54,954 --> 00:48:59,256
game and like Rihanna was saying she was part of the table read she was

989
00:49:00,132 --> 00:49:04,336
She was part of, how to say, putting the words to Lara,

990
00:49:04,336 --> 00:49:07,118
how she would react in the different situations.

991
00:49:07,118 --> 00:49:10,681
And the other actors on set would kind of key off her.

992
00:49:10,681 --> 00:49:12,923
She would be kind of a linchpin for the performance

993
00:49:12,923 --> 00:49:15,866
in the big moments of the story.

994
00:49:15,866 --> 00:49:19,969
But we did have

995
00:49:21,120 --> 00:49:23,322
reshoots of some of the scenes we had to go back.

996
00:49:23,322 --> 00:49:25,444
When we came back we found out it didn't work out

997
00:49:25,444 --> 00:49:29,086
in the user tests and so we would continuously

998
00:49:29,086 --> 00:49:31,368
kind of making this kind of puzzle of what are we reshooting?

999
00:49:31,368 --> 00:49:34,450
What are we kind of picking up in different ways

1000
00:49:34,450 --> 00:49:37,072
through VO or through the performances?

1001
00:49:37,072 --> 00:49:39,694
And sometimes having to even recast actors

1002
00:49:39,694 --> 00:49:40,655
because it didn't work.

1003
00:49:42,209 --> 00:49:48,392
We're trying to make a very, as I said, relatable world with kind of grounded characters and

1004
00:49:48,392 --> 00:49:52,614
sometimes with the VO sessions it would be hard to find actors that would be kind of

1005
00:49:52,614 --> 00:49:58,117
differently calibrated for different kinds of games to get that voice that was more kind

1006
00:49:58,117 --> 00:50:02,119
of in sync with the rest of the direction of the game.

1007
00:50:02,119 --> 00:50:06,941
So sometimes we would bring people back and say, okay, all that kind of bad guy voice,

1008
00:50:06,941 --> 00:50:11,844
just please get rid of it and just do your own voice and it would be actually a lot better.

1009
00:50:12,804 --> 00:50:15,547
Tor was critical in that he was able to be in most of the VO sessions,

1010
00:50:15,547 --> 00:50:18,529
and since he had such a strong understanding of the story,

1011
00:50:18,529 --> 00:50:21,672
was able to provide all that context for the actors, which is key,

1012
00:50:21,672 --> 00:50:24,674
because you can have a very well-written line and a very good actor.

1013
00:50:25,067 --> 00:50:27,388
And if they deliver it in the wrong context or in the wrong tone,

1014
00:50:27,388 --> 00:50:29,649
the scene completely falls flat.

1015
00:50:29,649 --> 00:50:32,170
So we were very lucky to have Tor in that position.

1016
00:50:32,170 --> 00:50:35,812
Now we try to obviously minimize those recasting and reshoots

1017
00:50:35,812 --> 00:50:38,973
by following this process and rigorously iterating.

1018
00:50:38,973 --> 00:50:40,634
But those things are going to happen,

1019
00:50:40,634 --> 00:50:42,875
and it was important that we embrace them and were agile

1020
00:50:42,875 --> 00:50:45,096
and willing to make those changes when we needed to.

1021
00:50:45,297 --> 00:50:49,398
Yeah, I mean, if you do your job right and you get to the end of this, then those, those reshoots are minimal.

1022
00:50:49,398 --> 00:51:02,521
And obviously not everyone's working on these giant projects, but, you know, I still think that the benefit of having, you know, a firm idea of your story before you start doing whatever version of the final assets is going to help you.

1023
00:51:02,521 --> 00:51:02,621
Yeah.

1024
00:51:02,621 --> 00:51:13,963
And speaking about finaling, uh, we had a, we were lucky enough to have an extremely talented cinematics team that was located in Montreal, uh, led by Dave Hubert, who, uh, helped.

1025
00:51:14,812 --> 00:51:19,154
bring all of this together in the package that you actually see when you play the game.

1026
00:51:19,154 --> 00:51:25,156
And Tor was talking about recasting, and sometimes we would have to make changes even after reshoots

1027
00:51:25,156 --> 00:51:25,817
were done.

1028
00:51:25,817 --> 00:51:30,359
And at that time, we had the animators up there, and they were very diligent and very

1029
00:51:30,359 --> 00:51:36,222
passionate about making sure that every detail on Lara's face and her actions was communicated

1030
00:51:36,222 --> 00:51:36,722
correctly.

1031
00:51:36,722 --> 00:51:37,222
And so...

1032
00:51:38,061 --> 00:51:42,327
As much as we have all this great motion capture technology and performance capture technology,

1033
00:51:42,327 --> 00:51:46,292
there's still an animator that's sitting there and is hand keying certain things in order to

1034
00:51:46,292 --> 00:51:50,197
bring it all together. And so we were just extremely fortunate to be working with them

1035
00:51:50,197 --> 00:51:52,440
up there and I just want to give a big shout out to them.

1036
00:51:54,475 --> 00:51:57,437
All right, so we've talked about our core story pillars

1037
00:51:57,437 --> 00:52:00,218
of Crystal Dynamics, the learnings we took from 2013's

1038
00:52:00,218 --> 00:52:02,859
Tomb Raider reboot, and a little bit about our process.

1039
00:52:02,859 --> 00:52:05,260
So here's our key takeaways we'd like

1040
00:52:05,260 --> 00:52:06,840
you to take from this talk.

1041
00:52:06,840 --> 00:52:09,041
The very important thing is that your process is key.

1042
00:52:09,041 --> 00:52:11,822
Create and embrace that process, whatever the project.

1043
00:52:11,822 --> 00:52:14,023
Obviously, your process isn't going to look exactly like

1044
00:52:14,023 --> 00:52:18,385
ours, but adapt or create one from the ground up, and stick

1045
00:52:18,385 --> 00:52:20,066
to it, and you're going to be able to make yourself a

1046
00:52:20,066 --> 00:52:21,666
roadmap to get there in the end.

1047
00:52:22,007 --> 00:52:24,508
Cultivate feedback from every area of the team.

1048
00:52:24,508 --> 00:52:25,709
Don't hold anything too precious.

1049
00:52:25,709 --> 00:52:27,430
Everybody's feedback is important.

1050
00:52:27,430 --> 00:52:29,591
And you need to be able to defend your ideas.

1051
00:52:29,591 --> 00:52:30,872
If you can't defend them, then they're not

1052
00:52:30,872 --> 00:52:32,293
worth keeping on the page.

1053
00:52:32,293 --> 00:52:33,894
You can't have a thin skin.

1054
00:52:33,894 --> 00:52:36,295
You've got to let everybody speak their mind bluntly,

1055
00:52:36,295 --> 00:52:38,877
however they're going to speak it, and take that to heart.

1056
00:52:38,877 --> 00:52:40,217
And then finally, be inclusive.

1057
00:52:40,217 --> 00:52:42,238
The entire team has a stake in the story.

1058
00:52:42,238 --> 00:52:43,939
Everything in the game tells a story.

1059
00:52:43,939 --> 00:52:46,701
I said that we are the team responsible

1060
00:52:46,701 --> 00:52:48,562
for the ultimate presentation of the narrative

1061
00:52:48,562 --> 00:52:49,383
in Rise of the Tomb Raider.

1062
00:52:49,883 --> 00:52:52,284
In reality, the entire team is the narrative team.

1063
00:52:52,284 --> 00:52:56,045
We are all telling the story of Lara and the world at the same time.

1064
00:52:56,045 --> 00:52:59,286
So thank you guys very much for coming.

1065
00:52:59,286 --> 00:53:03,287
I think we have a few moments for questions and then we'll be able to be in the wrap-up

1066
00:53:03,287 --> 00:53:04,387
area afterwards.

1067
00:53:04,387 --> 00:53:06,008
We have five minutes.

1068
00:53:06,008 --> 00:53:07,728
Does anybody want to step up and ask a question?

1069
00:53:07,728 --> 00:53:09,168
There we go, right to the mic.

1070
00:53:09,319 --> 00:53:23,718
Hi, so I'm a one-person team for a small game I'm working on, and I want to know what you would suggest for the feedback, the inclusive part, because if I'm a one-person team, I don't really have a lot of people to ask for feedback, so I'm just curious on what you would recommend for that.

1071
00:53:24,257 --> 00:53:25,818
Absolutely.

1072
00:53:25,818 --> 00:53:27,579
Well, I think my recommendation would

1073
00:53:27,579 --> 00:53:29,980
be to seek feedback from people that you know and you trust,

1074
00:53:29,980 --> 00:53:31,601
and people who are going to be honest to you.

1075
00:53:31,601 --> 00:53:34,422
If at all possible, get it in front of people

1076
00:53:34,422 --> 00:53:36,983
who aren't gamers, who are going to bring a different viewpoint

1077
00:53:36,983 --> 00:53:37,123
to it.

1078
00:53:37,123 --> 00:53:39,384
I think some of the most interesting story advice I got

1079
00:53:39,384 --> 00:53:41,625
was from environment artists, who

1080
00:53:41,625 --> 00:53:43,206
were telling me about the placement of objects

1081
00:53:43,206 --> 00:53:44,127
that I didn't even think about.

1082
00:53:44,127 --> 00:53:46,468
So being able to find somebody who maybe

1083
00:53:46,468 --> 00:53:48,168
has a unique viewpoint, you really

1084
00:53:48,168 --> 00:53:50,750
have to seek that out if you're on a team of one, absolutely.

1085
00:53:50,750 --> 00:53:51,270
Anybody else?

1086
00:53:53,332 --> 00:53:54,192
You like that answer, huh?

1087
00:53:54,192 --> 00:53:54,833
Yeah, good answer.

1088
00:53:54,833 --> 00:53:55,553
All right, terrific.

1089
00:53:55,553 --> 00:53:57,593
I would also recommend just making

1090
00:53:57,593 --> 00:53:58,894
sure to track your feedback.

1091
00:53:58,894 --> 00:54:01,034
Don't just have a casual conversation

1092
00:54:01,034 --> 00:54:04,716
and then just kind of retain it by asking the document where

1093
00:54:04,716 --> 00:54:07,156
they can, keep an Excel sheet or whatever tools

1094
00:54:07,156 --> 00:54:08,017
you use to track it.

1095
00:54:08,017 --> 00:54:10,257
But always go back and evaluate and make

1096
00:54:10,257 --> 00:54:11,878
sure that you're marking those things off the list

1097
00:54:11,878 --> 00:54:12,678
as you're developing.

1098
00:54:12,678 --> 00:54:13,238
Yeah, absolutely.

1099
00:54:13,238 --> 00:54:15,499
And even if you don't agree with the feedback,

1100
00:54:15,499 --> 00:54:19,580
you should understand it and put it down and internalize it.

1101
00:54:19,580 --> 00:54:19,900
Thank you.

1102
00:54:19,900 --> 00:54:20,620
Of course.

1103
00:54:22,081 --> 00:54:22,622
Hey.

1104
00:54:22,622 --> 00:54:23,623
Hi there.

1105
00:54:23,623 --> 00:54:26,486
So you talked about receiving feedback from the whole team.

1106
00:54:26,486 --> 00:54:29,150
I was wondering at what points in the process

1107
00:54:29,150 --> 00:54:31,973
you got feedback because sometimes early on,

1108
00:54:31,973 --> 00:54:34,036
small teams are good, and how you bring people in.

1109
00:54:35,469 --> 00:54:37,490
John, you want to take that?

1110
00:54:37,490 --> 00:54:40,170
Well, I try to seek feedback at every step,

1111
00:54:40,170 --> 00:54:41,430
even in that early phase.

1112
00:54:41,430 --> 00:54:44,851
I would tend to have meetings every week

1113
00:54:44,851 --> 00:54:47,692
where anybody on the team could come

1114
00:54:47,692 --> 00:54:49,352
and I would do an overview of the story.

1115
00:54:49,352 --> 00:54:54,974
And I'm all about taking the feedback and assessing it.

1116
00:54:54,974 --> 00:54:58,935
But I don't feel like excluding is something that

1117
00:54:58,935 --> 00:55:01,135
is ever going to be helpful.

1118
00:55:01,955 --> 00:55:05,996
I can separate the ideas that I'm getting from people, that we're getting from people,

1119
00:55:05,996 --> 00:55:10,357
and still hold on to our vision, and still have that small team. I mean, I understand what you're

1120
00:55:10,357 --> 00:55:15,659
saying, but I do think even, you know, you want the whole team to be with you, and you're going

1121
00:55:15,659 --> 00:55:19,420
to have a team, no matter how small your team is at the beginning, they're, you know, they're going

1122
00:55:19,420 --> 00:55:23,801
to be with you to the end, and you want them to carry the vision with you, and always be able,

1123
00:55:23,801 --> 00:55:25,641
you know, you want people on your team.

1124
00:55:27,619 --> 00:55:30,284
You want them challenging you, but you don't want them off the same page.

1125
00:55:30,284 --> 00:55:34,111
You all want to be kind of carrying the vision together, so I think it's important at every step.

1126
00:55:34,735 --> 00:55:36,915
And it blossoms when you get it in the game.

1127
00:55:36,915 --> 00:55:39,236
So we talk about standing it up for user test.

1128
00:55:39,236 --> 00:55:41,617
It's actually also, there's the small group who will give you

1129
00:55:41,617 --> 00:55:42,977
feedback on the page.

1130
00:55:42,977 --> 00:55:45,038
But as soon as it's on the screen, and even before we

1131
00:55:45,038 --> 00:55:47,199
would do moving pictures, sometimes we just put slates

1132
00:55:47,199 --> 00:55:49,819
up there so that people understood the story beat that

1133
00:55:49,819 --> 00:55:51,080
was going to be there.

1134
00:55:51,080 --> 00:55:53,901
And all of a sudden, everyone is now playing their game with

1135
00:55:53,901 --> 00:55:56,501
the story in it and having all kinds of ideas of how it could

1136
00:55:56,501 --> 00:55:58,222
be better or what they're not understanding yet.

1137
00:55:58,222 --> 00:56:01,243
So just dropping it in is an explosion of feedback.

1138
00:56:01,343 --> 00:56:03,925
And I would say it's definitely not a comfortable feeling.

1139
00:56:03,925 --> 00:56:06,247
I mean, it was insanely frustrating as a writer

1140
00:56:06,247 --> 00:56:09,150
and as a story person to get that constantly.

1141
00:56:09,150 --> 00:56:10,992
Like, you feel like you're under attack,

1142
00:56:10,992 --> 00:56:13,474
but you just kind of have to let it all come in.

1143
00:56:13,474 --> 00:56:15,115
And you know it's broken at that point.

1144
00:56:15,115 --> 00:56:17,598
This is early enough that it is not your perfect version.

1145
00:56:17,598 --> 00:56:20,260
And you have to stand there and hear about how

1146
00:56:20,260 --> 00:56:21,081
you know it's broken.

1147
00:56:21,081 --> 00:56:22,462
But occasionally, you'll hear about how

1148
00:56:22,462 --> 00:56:23,583
you don't know it's broken yet also.

1149
00:56:23,583 --> 00:56:25,224
And those are the precious ones.

1150
00:56:25,555 --> 00:56:29,537
It does make you really robust for writing for any other entertainment medium.

1151
00:56:29,537 --> 00:56:35,440
You are just writing in a headwind of feedback all the time.

1152
00:56:35,440 --> 00:56:36,720
Over & over again.

1153
00:56:37,445 --> 00:56:40,327
But yeah, it is really good for kind of thickening your skin.

1154
00:56:40,327 --> 00:56:46,171
And it became very important to us to open the process earlier.

1155
00:56:46,171 --> 00:56:48,933
And that was something that we took from Rise

1156
00:56:48,933 --> 00:56:51,654
so we could identify problems earlier in the process

1157
00:56:51,654 --> 00:56:52,915
and smooth things out.

1158
00:56:52,915 --> 00:56:55,397
Because we didn't always do that with the first game.

1159
00:56:55,397 --> 00:56:58,139
And that was something that we definitely carried through.

1160
00:56:58,139 --> 00:56:58,639
Open it up early.

1161
00:56:58,639 --> 00:57:00,080
Their problems will be there.

1162
00:57:00,080 --> 00:57:01,781
Those problems will be there.

1163
00:57:01,781 --> 00:57:04,503
So let's get to them early and sort them out early.

1164
00:57:04,503 --> 00:57:05,644
And I think that really helped.

1165
00:57:06,507 --> 00:57:08,048
OK, I think we're going to be available for more questions

1166
00:57:08,048 --> 00:57:09,209
in the wrap-up area after this.

1167
00:57:09,209 --> 00:57:10,891
But everybody, thank you so much for coming.

1168
00:57:10,891 --> 00:57:12,092
I'm supposed to remind you to fill out

1169
00:57:12,092 --> 00:57:13,353
an evaluation of some sort.

1170
00:57:13,353 --> 00:57:14,734
So please do that.

1171
00:57:14,734 --> 00:57:15,335
And thank you again.

